        <i>Verticillium dahliae</i>
    </div>
    <div class="container col-md-7 safety-panel"    id="sfty-acc8">
           <p>
                This year our project involves working with Verticillium wilt, a fungal plant pathogen caused by the facultative parasite ascomycete Verticillium dahliae. Getting to know the main characteristics of these fungi and developing the right containment methods to avoid accidental release has become indispensable for the correct development of our project. This telluric fungus remains in infested soils through spores or conidia, hyphae and microsclerotia. The infection results in reduced growth, epinastia, wilting, foliar chlorosis that can progress to necrosis, obscuration of xylematic vessels, and leaf abscission.
           </p>
           <p>
                According to DSMZ, it’s defined as the Risk 1 Group with low potential risk. 
                Biological safety and biocontainment practices includes wearing laboratory coat, gloves and eye protection, regular cleaning of work clothes, washing our hands after working with the pathogens and before leaving the laboratory, decontaminating work surfaces after completion of work and after any spill of the fungus leaving our personal belongings and food away from the lab when handling infectious materials and regular decontamination of laboratory equipment and materials. It should be noted that handling of this fungus was done by lighting a burner in the working area or in an ESCO Class II biosafety cabinet. This cabinet was only used after its cleaning with ethanol 70% (v/v) and exposition to UV light for fifteen minutes.
                
            </p>
